History of IBM: from cheese cutter to space flights
The company IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York a hundred years ago, being its original name Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was adopted already in 1924 - originally it was a brand used in the branches of Canada and South America.
The basis that gave rise to the birth of IBM stems from the merger of four companies dating back to the 1880s.
It had inventions such as the famous "file clock", which allows to control the entry and exit of employees.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who also chaired his supervisory board until 1930.
Flint appointed the head of a competition company, Thomas J. Watson, to assist him with the management of the company.
The new leader eclipsed IBM's founder ( Watson's ideas remain the firm foundation on which corporate culture and identity are based).
Watson led the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name indicates, began with the production and sale of all kinds of business equipment, from meat and cheese cutters to cash registers.
During the first four years that Watson led the company, the billing doubled by $9 million and began the great expansion of the company by the continents.
Watson was so crucial to the company that, almost forty years after occupying the chief's chair, he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, IBM staff and computers helped NASA guide flights to space (to Mercury, Saturn and in 1969 the famous Moon flight).
Meanwhile, in 1964 IBM developed the first generation of computers, the IBM System/360 series.
The classic "fishes", which established the computer standard of that time, arrived at the market with the name of IBM 5150 in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, which, for its part, acquired the consulting part of the company Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began offering a complete advice and services of high added value.
The strategy that IBM has paid for these last three years is the Smarter Planet concept, that is, "a smarter planet".
Its objective is to make the use of technology more rational, although the areas have not yet been planned and the circumstances, for example, with regard to transport and city administration, have not improved.
For the trade sector, IBM recently introduced the Smart Commerce platform that allows retailers to manage the full business cycle.
IBM has a long history in this country.
Already in 1932 he opened a branch in Czechoslovakia at the time, the first country to have it in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, IBM ČR also operates the strategic outsourcing centre in Brno.
The headquarters for Central and Eastern Europe is in Prague. Also here is a world-famous research team working with voice recognition.
