Before becoming the new face of the far right in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was simply another guy who aired his anti-immigration views online.
On Monday, Breivik, who admitted to killing in Norway in July, who left 77 dead, faced his first public court hearing.
While Breivik may have acted alone, he was far from alone in cyberspace: He had spent most of the time preceding his attack on his computer, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups on social networks.
After this summer's tragedy, researchers wanted to know more about these people.
But how do you find them?
Easy - you just have to go on Facebook.
"We realized that it wasn't that hard to reach them," says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of a recent report on European digital populism published by the UK DEMOS study centre.
Facebook's personal information list is so encyclopedic, says Bartlett, that researchers could simply use the advertising tool to determine their desired demographic characteristics with scientific precision - the way sellers have been using it for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million fans of right-wing groups across Europe and then directed ads to them, but instead of linking them to a new band or diet product, the ads invited users to complete a survey that asked about their educational level, attitudes towards violence and optimism about their own future.
On arriving through Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to study more than 10,000 followers of 14 far right parties in 11 European countries - all without leaving the office.
"It's a whole new way of doing an investigation," says Bartlett.
Some of the results are not entirely surprising: Online supporters of right-wing groups tend to be young, men and angry by immigration.
However, in a kind of turn, "those who combine their online activism with off-line activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who remain behind the computer screen."
DEMOS's work is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new and important tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centers, medical researchers and political scientists are using the site to study everything, from health problems to social trends as expressed in the "I like", messages on the walls and state updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three pieces of content a day, Facebook's "data supernova" is generating an increase in research, boosting the number of academic works with the name of the site in the title up to almost 800% in the last five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it allows you to study people you couldn't approach with a folder on the street.
"Before, when you were trying to survey people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
"You'd have to go through the game, and they'd never allow you access," says Bartlett.
"Facebook eliminates all that - you go to them directly."
Others say the site could provide a way to identify and address health-social problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin-Madison and her colleagues found that university students who spoke about their drinking efforts on Facebook had a significantly higher risk of having drinking problems than students who remained silent on the subject.
Moreno suggests that fellow students, such as residential counselors, could control the site and intervene to help a student publish too many state updates with his drunkards.
"You can't deal with a problem if you can't diagnose it," said Dimitri Christakis, Moreno's co-author and director of the Children's Health, Behavior and Development Center at the Seattle Children's Research Institute, the Washington Post.
"We have found a way to identify children at risk who would otherwise not be diagnosed."
Facebook is also constantly "pinching" its own population for data.
The Site's Data Team has developed statistics on the status of the relationship and Valentine's Day, the expectation of electoral participation in the middle of the 2010 legislative period, and a National Happiness Index (mainly using the information that can be accessed - defenders of digital freedom long ago argue that the site should make available to others its large amount of data for research).
However, Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not - the sacrifice for being able to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away is to allow the site to mine your personal information.
But what happens when Facebook users become part of a survey they don't even know?
While researchers have well-defined guidelines on how to collect their data offline, online is a free bar for everyone.
"I don't think many of the users have even thought about the fact that a researcher could be looking at their profiles," says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Laboratory, about a 2006 study that carried out with the student's Facebook public walls.
"As far as they were concerned, it was only between them and their friends."
