Legends about traps in school and university exams are widespread.
There have been cases in which teachers have given the exam responses to students in order to be better seen in their performance evaluations.
Mentors who should be teaching the opposite are sending the message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How much deception do we find?
On any day, studies show that they can lie to you anywhere from 10 to 200 times.
That's for sure, many of those lies are godly lies.
Another study showed that the unknown lied three times in the first 10 minutes of knowing each other.
Detecting lies, or "the location of lies", is an essential skill that we must all acquire, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a table game similar to, for example, Charada, where the goal is to exclaim: "I have you", the detection of deception is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data obtained over the past six decades at prestigious universities that carried out in-depth research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the investigation is that the old myths about lying have been refuted.
The liars do look into the eyes.
They don't always trembling, babbling, roaring, or restless.
Nor can it be concluded that liars are difficult to detect or unmask.
A trained lie detector can come to the truth by learning about the structure of the statement, the microfacial expressions, the formation of questions and the times.
I spent several years researching scientific discoveries about deception in the vast and ever emerging body of knowledge, and it was clear that detection of deception is a modern technique that is easy to learn and helps navigate our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, or negotiating management.
Good liars have the ability to read well to others, making them feel at ease, managing their own emotions and intuitively feeling how others perceive them.
We know from the research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men say more "minors oriented towards themselves", while women say more lies "oriented towards others" -- usually to protect someone's feelings -- than married people lie less frequently to their couples than people who are not married (but the lies they usually say tend to be "enormous").
We also know that if you are perceived as an evildoer, others will feel less guilty when lying to you.
How do I know if someone's lying?
First, observe the usual behavior of the subject.
This is called "creating a baseline."
Helps provide benchmarks to measure changes later.
Observe the subject's posture, laughter and vocal characteristic.
It's better to know if someone normally beats his foot all the time so he doesn't make unfair accusations when he sees his feet beating in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for deceptive, verbal and non-verbal behavior groups.
Consider these groups of behavior as alarm signals, not as evidence of deception.
People who cheat can freeze the top of the body by trying to remember their story, they can point their feet toward the door, lean towards an exit, change their posture significantly, or display a "post-interview shock" -- that exaggerated sigh of relief and change of posture once all the difficult questions have ended.
Interrogators often falsely show that the interview has ended only to seek that post-interview relief.
He also pays attention to the subject's vocabulary.
Scott Peterson put his foot down and used the time he spent while claiming that his murdered wife was alive, launching a search for her at the national level.
People who cheat can also use a remote language: "I didn't have sex with that woman... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "restrictive language" when he answers a difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... until I... understand myself."
This makes the answer a perception rather than a fact and is often a warning signal.
There is no magic formula to detect lies, but developing skills to discover deception is possible.
These skills will improve the chances of anyone to avoid being victimized by scam artists in their professional and personal lives.
