Climate adversity braked the economy
During the first year of management of Mario López Valdez, Sinaloa has increased unemployment and informality, lowered foreign investment and contracted the economy
2011 is a year that will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, it is the first year of government of Mario López Valdez, self-denominated of change, which generated great expectations regarding the progress in the economy, but given the climate adversity of the beginning of the year, no growth is observed, however there is a deterioration in the main indicators of economic development.
The low temperatures of February, in addition to causing millions of losses for the agricultural sector, limited the possibilities of the state economy to grow, caused a contraction of economic activity in general of 3.6 percent in the first half of the year, mainly justified by the historic fall of 31.16 percent in agriculture, which affected the dynamism of the other economic sectors.
According to the report of ice-cream impacts issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, 582,835 hectares were damaged, of which 78,03 per cent suffered total damage and the remaining 21.07 per cent suffered partial damage, the main sinister crops were those of vegetables, maize and chickpea.
The fall in economic activity has generated, until November, a steady increase in unemployment in the state, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, the rate of state unemployment during the first three quarters of the year was observed an accelerated growth, as while between January and March 55,053 people were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53 per cent of the economically active population, for the second quarter the rate became 5.28 per cent, and between July and September the average continued to increase to 6.19 per cent, a rate that in number casts more than 74 thousand unemployed people, an increase compared to the first half of 18,969 individuals.
Less liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, for economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the growth of unemployment can be explained indirectly, depending on the actions that have been carried out from public policy.
"What is being seen is an increase in unemployment that has to do with several factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market for the effects of a restriction of resources by the legislation that was passed at the congress to combat money laundering, as it is not easy for people who illegally grab dollars to work, invest and use them in something," he said.
Detained migration
López Cervantes pointed out that there is also a demographic factor in the rise in unemployment.
"The number of people leaving the state looking for work abroad, in the United States has been restricted, first because of the difficulties to enter, and second because entering already have many difficulties to find work, these people are staying and are demanding sources of work here in the state, which makes unemployment rise," he said.
Informality
The analysis of the Danish labour market is aggravated by considering the high level of informality that predominates among working conditions, according to INEGI, 60.38 per cent of the population employed in the state works without being listed as a worker before any social security institution.
Along with unemployment and informality, another of the state's labor lags is low wages, the entity has the lowest wages in the country, according to the records of the Mexican Social Security Institute and the Ministry of Labour and Social Security.
The average monthly income of the Danish workers was, until September, 5 thousand 352 pesos, well below the national average, located at 7 thousand 375 pesos.
FDI contraction
Along with the fall in economic activity and the increase in unemployment, during 2011 there was the largest decline in foreign direct investment in the last 10 years, according to the Secretariat of Economy from January to June of State FDI amounted to $630,697, representing a drop of 87.74 per cent compared to the $5,143,312 recorded during the same period of the previous year.
For its part, the Secretariat for Economic Development of the State Government accounts for a total investment of 17,280 million pesos in the year, mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
Debt
Faced with the economic contraction scenario, the government of the state requested in July the approval of a credit for 3 billion pesos, the same that would be destined for investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, in order to revive the economy, the approval of the local congress was for a sum of 2,600 million pesos, and until November they have not observed the benefits of indebtedness in any sector of the state economy.
Reactions
For business representatives, Mario López Valdés' first year of government shows a lack of government management capacity.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the National Chamber of Transformation Industry, said that during 2011 he lacked the harmonization of the wills of the various sectors, including the government of the state itself.
"The performance of the economy in Sinaloa during this year has been very poor, we have to work hard to recover the ground that we lost this year, in 2012 we have to redouble our efforts, we have failed to align the effort of everyone and above all the good and synchronized march of this new government team, we hope that next year will be much better," he said.
Economic slowness
Loredo López stated that events such as the ice creams of the beginning of the year stopped the state economy and restricted its performance and growth.
"The low economic flow is the product of several events, including frosts, one of the main effects has been a slow economy that does not turn fast enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows to have an acceptable level of flow in processes, products and services and therefore, at the end of the year we are closing well below the expectations we had," he mentioned.
Redefining vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederación Patronal of the Mexican Republic in Sinaloa, he said that it is necessary to cause the state to productive activities of greater dynamism.
"We have generally observed that we have been working, we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program that redefines the vocation and economic direction of the state, because it is important that the full potential of the material and human resource that Sinaloa has is detonated," he said.
Work to be done
The President of Coparmex stressed the importance of establishing a vision for the future that better addresses the efforts of the Government.
"In general terms, I would say that the Government has been striving to achieve good results in various areas, in the area of economic development there is some progress, but it is important that a long-term programme be developed," he said.
He noted that the current administration has shown progress in its conduct of public policy.
"There are elements to say that the Government is being more inclusive, I can say that there is work done and I believe that the Government is aware that there is work to be done," he said.
