The possibility of the "vote per vote" count is a reality with regard to this year's election process in Michoacán, where according to the data released by the Preliminary Electoral Results Program (PREP) the difference between the first and second place of the election of governor is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total minutes.
In this regard, the President of the General Council of the Electoral Institute of Michoacán (IEM), Maria de los Angeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, just last November 9, the electoral body adopted a series of guidelines in order to harmonize local rules with federal electoral reform.
As will be recalled, Michoacán did not approve his Political Constitution or the Electoral Code of the State or its Electoral Justice Act, since the Congress of the State approved the reforms shortly before the completion of the legal deadline for them to enter into force in the present electoral process, and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel failed to publish them within the time limits provided for in the Official Journal of the State Act, arguing that he had some objections.
On 9 November, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional dispute promoted by the local legislature and called it "invalid and illegal" the vote of the state's president on constitutional reforms, since he does not have the right to "sanction or veto them".
Interviewed about the possibility of "vote by vote", Maria de los Angeles Llanderal explained that thanks to the adoption of the corresponding guidelines by the General Council of the IEM it will be possible to carry out partial and total counts of the vote by the local electoral body.
In this way, the partial count of votes, of one or more electoral packages, may be given on the assumption that: the results of the minutes do not coincide; there is no record of scrutiny and counting in the file of the box or does not work in the possession of the president of the same; or, where there are obvious errors or alterations of the minutes.
In addition, the total count of the vote received in all the ballot boxes of the election may be made where there is evidence that the difference between the candidate who is presumed to be the winner of the election in question and the candidate who obtained the second place in the ballot is equal to or less than one percentage point; provided that at the beginning of the session there is an express request from the party representative and/or coalition who applied to the second of the candidates indicated.
The total count of the vote may also be made if at the end of the ordinary count it is established that the difference between the candidate allegedly winning and the candidate located in second place is equal to or less than one percentage point, provided that there is an express request from the representative of the political party whose candidate was second, in which case the electoral packages that have been partially counted will be excluded.
It should be mentioned that in this situation there is the choice of Morelia, where according to the PRSP the difference between the first and the second place is only 0.16%, although without counting the votes of 129 of the 923 total minutes.
