MSS announces protocol to find obesity gene
Leads Social Security an investigation to discover the gene of obesity in children and young people; it is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) announced that it is conducting a research to discover the gene of obesity in children and young people, called the 'Genetic Protocol on Obesity of Childhood and Adolescents', which will allow for markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Biochemistry Medical Research Unit of the Specialty Hospital of the National Medical Center of the 21st Century, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was integrated.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
In the investigation, the population is invited to participate in the study, whether or not it is entitled, to attend the sports units participating in the IMSS in the Valle de México, where the tests are carried out for minors, every Saturday from 8 a.m.
He pointed out that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (State of Mexico Poniente) and that since 8 October, the activity has been carried out in the Nezahualcoyolt Sports Unit (State of Mexico East).
Once the goal of bringing together 500 or 600 minors is met, the study will continue in the Independent Sports Unit (south of the Federal District) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (north of the Federal District).
He explained that the purpose of this research is to know the components and importance of genetics with respect to the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in Mexican children and young people to prevent the emergence of chronic degenerative diseases.
As World Diabetes Day was celebrated on 14 November, the goal was to bring together 3,000 children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the implementation of specific food questionnaires.
They will also be asked about the physical activity and family history of diseases, in order to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He explained that Saturdays apply to all participants anthropometric measurements (weight, size, waist circumference), blood pressure, determination of glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin levels and genetics (the aim is to identify genes that are associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López pointed out that this research is due to the concern of health professionals for the alarming weight gain in minors.
'The 1999 and 2006 health surveys indicated that in just six years there was an increase, in the case of boys, of 77 per cent in obesity, and of girls of 47 per cent; in terms of overweight, a dramatic increase was also observed,' said IMSS specialist.
He indicated that the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the population of the country differs from others because of its genetic history.
He reported that on average, Mexicans have 65 percent American Indian inheritance, 30 percent European and five percent African, and this condition is reflected in genes associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity translates into the inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) and that it is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit to participants is the comprehensive assessment of children, which allows for the detection of any degree of overweight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark-colored folds (acantosis) in the neck and forearm, which indicate the likelihood of metabolic alterations and even prediabetes.
The information is handled confidentially, the doctors hand it over in writing to the parents, to whom each of the measurements and lifestyle changes they must make to prevent disease are explained.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentaryism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, stay most of the day sitting in front of the television and use means of transport instead of walking short distances.
It is also due to high caloric intake, i.e. the increased consumption of sugary drinks, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburger, etc.) with high fat and protein content and the genetics that is analyzed in this protocol.
UNAM asphalt would avoid bumps
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry, develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signs sent by the pavement were met, it would not be necessary to repair nearly 200,000 basins each rainy season in the Metropolitan Area of the Valley of Mexico, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher of the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of UNAM, who assured that if the process of construction and maintenance of an asphalt floor is the right one, the basins could be reduced in quantity or even completely eliminated.
In his lecture A technological opinion of the baches, dictated within the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, revealed that the laboratory in charge develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Najera estimated that this type of modified asphalts could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, like some cities in the north of the country, to improve their performance and therefore the formation of bumps.
He explained that asphalt, the heavier part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbons molecules, some of them of high molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and others of low molecular weight, called Maltese, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of asphalt is that at high temperatures, about 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees centigrade its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees centigrade it has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
This means that in the streets the resistance of asphalt is not uniform, but is changing during the day according to environmental and temperature conditions, the specialist in chemical engineering warned.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered by flexible pavement, which consists of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Among the most superficial layers is the asphalt folder, made up of small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the stones that constitutes the folder, pointed out, is bathed with asphalt.
By transiting the vehicles and generating efforts, it allows the forces to spread very well on the pavement.
If it were modified asphalt, it would spread even better, the chemical engineer said.
On the asphaltic folder, it abounded, a last layer called rolling folder is placed, which is made of a fine stone material, that is, a sand that also bathes in asphalt.
Since it is the layer that will be in contact with the wheels of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt folder and provide friction on the road.
Being the part of the pavement that will receive and spread the efforts, the rolling folder also requires to have the proper thickness and care should be taken of the material that is made of.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he said, because it significantly affects the performance of the asphaltic folder.
When the soil is wet, the water is diffused inside the folder and it is difficult to get out, this causes a softening of all layers of the pavement and therefore the formation of patches.
In the process of forming a batch, he said, the first one to wear is the rolling film and only afterwards is affected the asphalt folder, but the damage does not happen instantly, but it is a process that should be attended to the first signs with proper maintenance programs.
The member of the National Researcher System also explained that the vehicle load is another important factor in the formation of bumps and, therefore, the thickness of each layer of the pavement must always go in relation to the vehicle load and ensure that it is fulfilled, in order to avoid frequent bumps.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still a lot to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, asphalt emulsions, which in other countries are already found even in the market and allow repairing batches easily and without needing to use high temperatures.
