However, it is rarely economically analyzed.
The point is that, on this subject, there is quite a consensus between the left and the right.
In the case of the right, Jacques Chirac fixed the orientation stating in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem for a country that has about two million immigrant workers", while on the left, the tone set it Michel Rocard explaining that France "can't take care of all the misery of the world" in 1990.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, both the left and the right shared the fear of invasion of the national territory by a multitude of Polish plumbers.
On both sides, immigrants are considered to be a burden on the French economy and society.
The only difference is in the degree of generosity with which they act with respect to immigrants.
In his program, François Hollande merely includes trivialities, indicating that co-development will solve the "problem of migration".
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may be profitable electorally, but economically it comes out very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent work summarizing the latest knowledge about immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among specialists on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries receiving immigrants.
The limitation of immigration weakens growth and undermines employment.
Fears related to the impact of immigrants are based on the idea that they can replace national workers, in particular the low-skilled, by pushing for their wages to be reduced.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are more complementary than substitutes for national workers and are mainly engaged in occupations in sectors with a lack of employment.
Unskilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national workers and the most skilled in dynamic sectors where training does not meet the demand for staff.
A positive effect on wages
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country that lacks anaesthetics, complementarity between nationals and immigrants causes the arrival of the latter to have a positive impact on the salaries and employment of nationals.
Taking this into account, Giovanni Peri estimated that an increase of 1% in migration flows represents an increase in real long-term wages of between 0.6 and 0.9 per cent.
And, regardless of the fact that the diversity that immigrants bring contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (there is a large proportion of naturalized American Nobel Prizes and companies such as Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Immigrants are also net contributors to social systems, as they provide an average of 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The International Labour Organization estimates, for example, that in Germany an immigrant who reaches the age of 30 years will make a net contribution (low-cost income) of EUR 150,000 to public average budgets throughout his life.
At the beginning of his tenure, Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to go look for the growth points that he lacked "with his teeth".
These teeth, which dissuade immigrants, had exactly the opposite effect.
