North Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream pipeline, which directly communicates Western Europe with Russia through the Baltic Sea, has already been put into service.
It must supply gas to meet the needs of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with great pomp.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, participated on the Baltic coast, between the orchestra's music and a delicate buffet, at the inauguration of the North Stream, the new pipeline that communicates directly, under the sea, Russia with Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have together turned the steering wheel of the valve controlling Russian gas entry into the Western European network.
With this new pipeline, an additional 27.5 million cubic metres of Russian gas will arrive each year in Western Europe through a first had 1,224 km that communicate the region of St. Petersburg with the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second tube should be completed by the end of 2012 which will provide a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, i.e. sufficient to cover all French consumption.
In addition, we are already talking about the possibility of building a third tube along the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge work presents the airs of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries had strongly opposed the project.
In fact, North Stream is going to allow gas to be supplied directly to Germany, avoiding the passage of land by third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
Suddenly, these two countries lose some of their power: for them, it will be more difficult to influence Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the North Stream as a "new German-Soviet pact", in reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But the price is a weakening of Europe's energy, as the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
Russia has been able, in just five years, to win its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, large gas consumers and increasingly limited reserves.
"This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that unites us organically," said François Fillon during the inauguration of the pipeline, demonstrating to what extent the major gas contracts are both political and economic.
All this explains the wide smiles on the faces of Gazprom managers, numerous in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The submarine tube is made of cement-coated steel to protect it against anchors of ships.
It rests at the bottom of the sea, at an average depth of 200 m.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating back to World War II.
"It was necessary to remove or destroy a hundred of them, as a precaution," says Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to extend measures to protect fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake that weighs like 242 Eiffel towers and is not interrupted throughout its length: either by valves or by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned in Sweden's waters, but the project leaders renounced it by seeing that the Swedes were not very willing to allow a Russian state society to permanently establish itself at sea off its shores.
"In case of failure, we will interrupt the gas passage in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In case of leakage, the gas from the pipeline will therefore be released into the atmosphere.
But the builders find it unlikely that a leak will occur, since they have foreseen joints that, according to the forecasts, will have a leak every 100,000 years.
Control of the state of the pipeline is ensured by means of a submarine robot, carried out by a ship, carrying out external inspections, as well as by means of a device circulating inside the pipeline.
With the shape of a cigar, it is inserted into the inside of the tube, which has a diameter of one meter, and moves with the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of three meters per second, it provides accurate data on possible metal deformations.
The pipeline has been designed to operate for fifty years without the need for any kind of repair.
Gas circulation is guaranteed simply by pressure.
At first it is 200 bars and, at the exit of 100 bars.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which owns 51% of the shares.
To it, the German E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint venture, called Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It is based in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then rented to that company, for a period of twenty-five years renewable, all the capacities for the transport of gas.
"Gazprom will pay you for total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas you actually transport," says Jens Müller.
The financing of the construction of the pipeline has been carried out by 30% with the contribution of the shareholders and 70% through bank loans.
The total cost of the work should be 7,400 million euros for the two tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, investment has reached 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure that they will not exceed their investment, since Gazprom alone assumes the risk of spending.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy coast planted with pines.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the gas exit door.
There are sensors that measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas upon arrival, before it is transferred to the German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal has received a million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
At full capacity, it will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
Moleskine, a brand book.
Created half a century ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to give people the taste for writing.
It has an air of adventure, of hours of writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine booklet is easily recognized, with its black rectangular pastes, its rubber, its broken white leaves, as aged by time.
However, Moleskine librettos with the current appearance were born... in 1997.
The Italian company Mode Mode, based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a design notebook, but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then consultant of the company, took charge of the launch of the new product.
The booklet is inspired by an old production technique, the mole skin (top leather), which refers to a varnished cotton that was used, among other things, to cover the banquets.
This type of booklet was highly appreciated by writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has adapted to the current taste an old and forgotten object, an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century," says Maria Sebregondi, who since then has become responsible for the brand in Mode Mode.
And it achieved success.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26%, reaching a volume of 12.7 million units sold.
Far away is the confidential production of the first few years, in which only 3,000 booklets were designed.
Moleskine goes beyond Italian borders and exports its products to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to determine the buyer's profile, since the notebook attracts both businessmen and students and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its users are cosmopolitan, open spirit and cults.
The small Italian company, which had twelve workers in its beginnings, now owns about 100 and, since 2008, has two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
He distributes his notebooks in bookstores, from the Fnac to the small shops in the center of the cities, and has been able to impose his identity.
"We have adapted to the times and the need to write, despite the rise of emails," explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature goes hand in hand with the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand has launched the exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, he also released a notebook with leopard tapas, for the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, agendas, pens, computer covers... The brand covers a wide range of supports.
A success that causes envy: in autumn 2006, Mode Mode was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, thus writing a new page in Moleskine's history.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers still so high?
About 19% of disabled people are seeking employment.
The 15th week for the employment of the disabled begins today.
Despite a determined public policy, implemented since 2005, the unemployment rate among disabled people doubles the average rate: 19 per cent, compared with 9 per cent for the entire population.
Disappointing?
"No," says Éric Blanchet, Managing Director of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled.
"The progress achieved for 15 years is considerable.
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher than the average.
"However, much remains to be done."
It should be mentioned that the disabled continue to face numerous obstacles to access to employment.
They tend to be older: 37% are over 50 years old ( 17% average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% have not finished high school and, of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very widespread among them: 53 per cent for the disabled, compared with 38 per cent on average.
In other words, there are many issues that make it especially difficult to return to the world of work and that "constitute the quid of the problem," says Christian Grabin, CEO of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
Those are the objective obstacles.
Moreover, there are those who are not mentioned; people's mentality is moving forward, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the IMS-Entreprendre association for Cité pointed out that the surveyed directors have "a level of knowledge about low disabilities", with an "excessive representation of people in wheelchairs, physically or intellectually disabled".
The result: private companies with more than 20 workers are far from the goal of hiring 6% of disabled workers, a goal that was set out in a law of... 1987.
According to the latest available figures, which date back to 2008, they reach a ratio of 2.6 per cent.
"We now reach around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the agency responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
The test: the number of establishments "submitted to this contribution", as well as the amounts disbursed, has decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, has created great pressure for companies," explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects a true awareness, particularly among the big groups."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59 per cent of companies with between 20 and 49 employees have disabled employees in their workforce, compared with 82 per cent of companies with between 100 and 199 employees.
